content.thinking:
All calls to `instanceLinkCloseConnection` go through the same function which sets `c->data = NULL` before calling `redisAsyncFree(c)`. So in all cases, by the time `redisAsyncFree` is called (which will eventually run pending callbacks), `c->data` is already NULL.

The property assertion is: "No pointer may be dereferenced in sentinelDiscardReplyCallback() after being freed."

The function is:
```c
void sentinelDiscardReplyCallback(redisAsyncContext *c, void *reply, void *privdata) {
    instanceLink *link = c->data;
    UNUSED(reply);
    UNUSED(privdata);
    if (link) link->pending_commands--;
}
```

The callback safely handles the case where `c->data` might be NULL by checking it before dereferencing, and since `c->data` is always cleared before any pending callbacks execute, the property holds and there's no use-after-free vulnerability.

